const summaries = { lastRace: "Timo torched Canada with 72 points — more than triple the league average of 22 — with Kimi Antonelli alone dropping 62 of them in a dominant display. Mary Beth surged to a race-best 53, Hamilton picking up Driver of the Day, while Charlie collapsed to -42 as Alonso's massive DNF penalty dragged both drivers into the gutter. Margaret and Alyssa were the big disappointments, posting 12 and 15 respectively — well below the pack — as Russell's DNF and Perez's penalty wiped out what should have been solid weekends.", season: "Timo is running away with the league at 310 points, a commanding 89 ahead of second-place Margaret (221), and Antonelli's relentless consistency makes it hard to see who stops him. Cecelia is quietly holding fourth with five eerily steady scores between 32 and 42, while Charlie is the only manager in negative territory at -20, with Alonso's string of DNFs doing the damage. Mary Beth's last two races (37+53) are her best stretch yet and hint at a late charge, but the gap to the top three is steep.", players: { "Alyssa": "Third overall at 191, and it's basically the Verstappen show — Max has 155 points while Perez has scraped together just 36, including a CAN DNF that cost you badly. You've beaten the league average in three of five races, but Perez needs to stop actively hurting you if you want to close the gap on Margaret.", "Nora": "Fifth at 141, and the season has been a genuine redemption arc — Piastri's back-to-back DNFs to open the year put you in a hole, but he and Colapinto have combined for three straight above-average race scores to claw you back. Both drivers are now pulling weight almost equally (Piastri 75, Colapinto 66), which is a healthy sign for the run-in.", "Jay": "Seventh at 100, propped up almost entirely by Norris (95 pts) while Bottas has delivered a season total of just 5 — a true anchor. Norris's two DNFs have been the difference between top-four and treading water, and until you get clean weekends from both seats, the ceiling here is frustratingly low.", "Margaret": "Second at 221 and the most consistent threat to Timo — Russell (157) has been a rock and Ocon's 64 is quietly valuable support. CAN was your only real blip when Russell DNF'd and dropped you to 12, but five races of near-elite scoring means you're the only manager realistically chasing the leader.", "Cecelia": "Fourth at 179 and the smoothest operator in the league — your race scores read 42, 37, 34, 34, 32, which is almost suspiciously tidy. Leclerc (165) is doing nearly all the work while Bortoleto (14) has been hampered by DNFs, so one bad Leclerc weekend could shake that lovely consistency curve pretty hard.", "Timo": "League leader at 310 and it's not close — Antonelli alone has 254 points, including a 68-point explosion in China when your team posted a ridiculous 102-point round. Bearman's JPN DNF was the only real blemish on an otherwise dominant season, and barring a catastrophe, this title is yours to lose.", "Mary Beth": "Sixth at 128, with Hamilton (154) doing everything while Stroll (-26) buried you with three DNFs in the first three races and never truly recovered. The silver lining is real though — your last two rounds total 90 points, your best two-race stretch of the season, and Hamilton's CAN form with Driver of the Day suggests you're finally clicking.", "Jane": "Ninth at 67, with Lawson (61) carrying the load while Hadjar has contributed just 6 points all year despite flashes of promise. Your scoreline — -3, 54, 15, -28, 29 — is the most volatile in the league, and MIA's double-DNF disaster is the reason you're sitting this low despite some genuinely good weeks.", "David": "Eighth at 83, with Sainz (71) being a reliable grinder and Albon (12) costing you with DNFs in China and Canada. Your scores are frustratingly capped — only one race above 39 — and without a breakthrough week from one of your drivers, you're likely stuck in this mid-table purgatory.", "Charlie": "Dead last at -20, the only manager in negative territory, and Canada made it worse with a -42 disaster as Alonso took a brutal DNF penalty and Lindblad also failed to fire. Alonso sits at -23 for the season and is actively dragging you down — your four best races without him would leave you looking dramatically healthier.", "Sarah": "Tenth at 22, with Gasly (53) keeping your head just above water while Hulkenberg (-31) has been one of the most damaging picks in the league. Your -37 in Miami was the second-lowest single-race score of the entire season, and with both drivers blowing hot and cold, a meaningful points surge looks very difficult to engineer." } };
